>>45525923
It depends upon how well the worldbuilding is done. If it's believable, I'm agnostic on it.

More generally, the more reasonable worldbuilding I've seen to date has included some sort of human population because, where the fuck did humans come from? An Isekai story still has a world of humans somewhere, just on the other side of a portal or something.

For a story with anthro/other/alien races, I find it more plausible that humans are a minority race. In fact, all the races are "minority" in the sense that none are 50% or more of a population. there might be localized exceptions, cities or communities or enclaves, but I usually envision a world with about a dozen to 20 or so species, where maybe 3 or 4 make up a total of 60%/70% of the population and the remaining 10 or 15 races the rest. Humanity is part of the latter group, relatively rare and exotic, highly desirable for several reasons, which can vary depending on the story & setting, etc.

If you get all Star Trek about it, the galaxy might have a predominant type (humans or otherwise), but the particular world or section of the galaxy for a story, to me, is more fun if humans are a fragile minority, maybe even persecuted, and have to survive based upon intelligence and skillz.
